"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-12658/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-12658/canvas/1/c323f55b-50d2-44f7-8a0f-03d0164df77b","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T18:01:10.770Z","creator":"lucia","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>Although Alma is part of the House of Woodcock, is in a relationship with Reynolds, and contributes to the business of making dresses, her costume here makes her stand out. She does not wear the same cloaks as the rest of the seamstresses. Her unwieldy nature—represented by her clothes—makes it impossible for her to integrate into Reynolds’s house and life without bringing some disorder with her.&nbsp;</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-12658/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:72.46753246753246,168.31168831168833,1824.1558441558443,846.2337662337663"}}}]}]}]}